# What are HTML and CSS?

HTML (the Hypertext Markup Language) and CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) are two of the core technologies for building Web pages. HTML provides the structure of the 
page, CSS the (visual and aural) layout, for a variety of devices. Along with graphics and scripting, HTML and CSS are the basis of building Web pages and Web 
Applications. 

# Guide to HTML:
One of the first things you need to know is that HTML uses a tag-based system. These tags are what the browser reads to display what you have coded.
One of the most basic HTML 5 skeletons you'll encounter is displayed below:

<!DOCTYPE html> - This is a declaration saying we are going to use HTML code inside of it
<html> - We are including all our HTML code inside of it. The <> are HTML tags and there are opening and closing tags. I.E. Opening = <html> and Closing = </html>
<head> - Head tag is the set up of the page but is invisble to the user. You can only see it if you go to view source on a browser. 
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Page Title</title>
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
</head>
<body>
    <!-- <h1 style="color: red;">Hey from HTML</h1> -->  - To add a comment
</body>
</html>

# Div Tags
In HTML, div and span tags are elements used to define parts of a document, so that they are identifiable when a unique classification is necessary.
The more divs you have the more control you are going to have when it comes to selecting elements on the page.

<body>
  <h1>Hi there again</h1>

  <div>
    My content goes here
  </div>
</body>

# CSS Styles

# There are three main ways that you can use CSS code: Inline, Internal and External.
Inline - by using the style attribute inside HTML elements. I.E. <h1 style="color:blue;">A Blue Heading</h1>
Internal - by using a <style> element in the <head> section. I>E. body {background-color: powderblue;}
External - by using a <link> element to link to an external CSS file. I.E. <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">

# Inline Components with the Span Tag
<div>
My first type of content
<span>My amazing content</span>
</div>   

# Headings into Web Pages
<h1></h1>

# Multi Line Content with Paragraph Tags
<p> My first type of content </p>

